Compare CRISPR delivery vectors: AAV vs lipid nanoparticles — which is more clinically viable? {
"conclusion": "Lipid nanoparticles (LNPs) are more clinically viable for systemic CRISPR therapies because they deliver transient mRNAs rather than persistent viral genomes; while eranacogene dezaparvovec proves AAV can work in some contexts, the inherent averson and pre-existing immunity to both the capsid and Cas-related DNA components creates an unacceptable failure pathway for liver and other large targets—a ceiling LNP sidesteps by using cleaner mRNA formulations."
